<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900406-0025</DOCNO><DOCID>900406-0025.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- GLI Holding Co.:   Sixty Fired by Greyhound   For Strike-Related Violence</HL><DATE>04/06/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>TRANSPORTATION, TRUCK AND SHIP LINES, RAILROADS (TRA)</IN><LP>   Greyhound Lines Inc., Dallas, said it had fired 60employees for incidents of violence and vandalism associatedwith the strike by 9,300 members of the Amalgamated TransitUnion. Company spokesman George Gravley said the company wasprocessing a &quot;very large number&quot; of complaints that wouldresult in additional terminations.   The action came a day after a suspicious fire erupted at aGreyhound terminal in Boston. Since the strike began onMarch2, 29 Greyhound buses and terminals have been struck bygunfire, and the company has received 81 bomb threats. Inaddition, one striker driver has been killed and onereplacement was seriously injured.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Gravley described as &quot;talk and not action&quot; a statementissued earlier in the day by ATU President James La Sala, whocondemned the violence as &quot;reprehensible.&quot; Greyhound, a unitof GLI Holding Co., has said it will not return to thebargaining table until a week passes without violence.   Regarding that stance, Mr. La Sala complained that: &quot;Anycrackpot can stop negotiations from resuming by calling in aphone threat or by taking a potshot at a bus.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>